@etianen this might be a naive question, but why do we care if a directory exists? When you write files to s3, you need two things the key and the value. The key can be "blah" or something like "foo/bar/blah", they are the same according to s3, unlike a normal filesystem, you don't need to have the directory structure built up before you save the file in a directory.

Is it so that we can create empty directories on s3? 

Looking at the other django s3 storage libraries they don't seem to care about directories in their exists, but they are doing something a little different, they are using bucket.Object('key').load() and if that fails they return false. The Object().load() will throw an error if it is a directory which returns false if a directory exists.

If that happens what is the worse thing, it tries to create the key/directory again? Since it is empty, it might not be a big deal.

#### Code from django-storages: s3boto3.exists()

https://github.com/jschneier/django-storages/blob/master/storages/backends/s3boto3.py#L457-L472

```
   def exists(self, name):
        if not name:
            try:
                self.bucket
                return True
            except ImproperlyConfigured:
                return False
        name = self._normalize_name(self._clean_name(name))
        if self.entries:
            return name in self.entries
        obj = self.bucket.Object(self._encode_name(name))
        try:
            obj.load()
            return True
        except self.connection_response_error:
            return False
```

